IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. SIMPLE-FILE-RENAMER.
AUTHOR. SIMON MIKKELSEN.

* This program is designed to rename files. It takes an old filename
* and a new filename as input and renames the file accordingly.
* The program is written in COBOL, a language known for its verbosity
* and strict syntax. The purpose of this program is to demonstrate
* file handling in COBOL.

ENVIRONMENT DIVISION.
INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION.
FILE-CONTROL.
    SELECT OLD-FILE ASSIGN TO "OLD-FILE.TXT"
     ORGANIZATION IS LINE SEQUENTIAL.
    SELECT NEW-FILE ASSIGN TO "NEW-FILE.TXT"
     ORGANIZATION IS LINE SEQUENTIAL.

DATA DIVISION.
FILE SECTION.
FD  OLD-FILE.
01  OLD-FILE-RECORD PIC X(100).

FD  NEW-FILE.
01  NEW-FILE-RECORD PIC X(100).

WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01  WS-OLD-FILENAME PIC X(100).
01  WS-NEW-FILENAME PIC X(100).
01  WS-UNUSED-VARIABLE PIC X(100).
01  WS-ANOTHER-UNUSED-VARIABLE PIC X(100).
01  WS-LOTR-VARIABLE PIC X(100).

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
MAIN-PROCEDURE.
    DISPLAY "Enter the old filename: ".
    ACCEPT WS-OLD-FILENAME.
    DISPLAY "Enter the new filename: ".
    ACCEPT WS-NEW-FILENAME.

    OPEN INPUT OLD-FILE.
    OPEN OUTPUT NEW-FILE.

    PERFORM UNTIL EOF
     READ OLD-FILE INTO OLD-FILE-RECORD
         AT END
          MOVE "YES" TO EOF
     END-READ
     WRITE NEW-FILE-RECORD FROM OLD-FILE-RECORD
    END-PERFORM.

    CLOSE OLD-FILE.
    CLOSE NEW-FILE.

    DISPLAY "File renamed successfully from " WS-OLD-FILENAME " to " WS-NEW-FILENAME.

    STOP RUN.

EOF SECTION.
01  EOF PIC X VALUE "NO".

